## **Creating Registers from Structure Members**

You learned how to **access peripheral registers** (like `GPIOA_MODER`, `GPIOA_ODR`) **using C structures**, instead of manually calculating register addresses with `#define`.

Using our house and room analogy:

* The **peripheral** (e.g., `GPIOA`, `RCC`) is like a **house**.  
* The **C structure** is a **blueprint** üß± of that house ‚Äî it defines all the rooms/registers.  
* The **individual registers** inside the peripheral (e.g., `MODER`, `ODR`) are like the **rooms** inside the house.  
* The **structure members** represent those **registers/rooms**, and they are placed in the exact same order and layout as they exist in memory.

In the previous lesson, we accessed registers like this:

**\#define** **GPIOD\_MODE\_R** (\*(**volatile** **unsigned** **int** \*)(GPIOD\_BASE \+ MODE\_R\_OFFSET))

But in this lesson, you learned a cleaner and more maintainable way using **C structures** like this:

| typedef struct {    volatile uint32\_t MODER;    volatile uint32\_t OTYPER;    volatile uint32\_t OSPEEDR;    volatile uint32\_t PUPDR;    volatile uint32\_t IDR;    volatile uint32\_t ODR;    volatile uint32\_t BSRR;    volatile uint32\_t LCKR;    volatile uint32\_t AFR\[2\]; *// AFRL and AFRH*} GPIO\_TypeDef; |
| :---- |

#### **‚úÖ 1\. We define the structure**

When we create a structure for any peripheral, **we arrange the registers according to the memory address, one after another**.   
As shown below, how we have mapped from the reference manual to the actual code.

The order has to be maintained.

![][image1]

Each register is **32 bit** in size, and our members of the structure are also **uint32\_t.**  
This means each register will occupy 4 bytes in memory, and in the same way each structure member will occupy 4 bytes.

In the reference manual, you can see that, **offset of each register from the previous one is of 4 bytes**

**Structure members** are laid out in **consecutive memory**; here they are 4-byte aligned.

If we change the data type of any single member (say, **uint16\_t**), then everything will fall apart.

![][image2]

If we want to use only two registers, we can modify the structure as follows

Adding **DUMMY\[4\],** a 4-byte array, will act as padding.

If you want to skip unused registers, you **must** add dummy variables or arrays to keep the correct offsets.

E.g., if `ODR` starts at offset `0x14`, you must "fill" that gap in the struct with 4 dummy `uint32_t` values.

**typedef** **struct**  
{  
 \_\_IO **uint32\_t** MODER;    /\*\!\< GPIO port mode register,               Address offset: 0x00      \*/  
 \_\_IO **uint32\_t** DUMMY\[4\]; /\*Added 4(**uint32\_t)**\*4(4 elements) \= 16 DUMMY bytes to arrange the memory according to ref. manual\*/  
 \_\_IO **uint32\_t** ODR;      /\*\!\< GPIO port output data register,        Address offset: 0x14      \*/  
} **GPIO\_TypeDef**;

Without correct offsets ‚Üí memory access bugs (writing to wrong place\!).

Similarly, we only want to use one register from RCC

**typedef** **struct**  
{  
  \_\_IO **uint32\_t** DUMMY\[12\]; /\*Added 12\*4 DUMMY bytes to arrange the memory according to ref. manual\*/  
  \_\_IO **uint32\_t** AHB1ENR;       /\*\!\< RCC AHB1 peripheral clock register,                          Address offset: 0x30 \*/  
} **RCC\_TypeDef**;

#### **‚úÖ 2\. We make it point to the real address**

Now we need to make the structure accessible.  
We need to convert it to actual register

We created a structure with all GPIO register members‚Ä¶ but how do we **use it** in our code?

**GPIO\_TypeDef** and **RCC\_TypeDef** structures tells the compiler:

"Here‚Äôs the **blueprint** (or shape/layout) of a GPIO peripheral ‚Äî how its **registers** are arranged."

But this **does not yet point to any specific GPIO peripheral in memory** ‚Äî it‚Äôs just a **template**.

In STM32, `GPIOD` is nothing but **address** which starts at `0x40020C00`.

**\#define** **GPIOD\_BASE**			(AHB1PERIPH\_BASE \+ GPIOD\_OFFSET)

When we write:

**\#define** **GPIOD** ((GPIO\_TypeDef\*)GPIOD\_BASE)

This is like saying:

‚ÄúPlease **treat** the address `0x40020C00` GPIOD\_BASE as a pointer to GPIO\_TypeDef.‚Äù

((GPIO\_TypeDef\*)GPIOD\_BASE) Casts the hardware address to a structure pointer

* `GPIOD` is now a **pointer** to our structure.  
* We use `GPIOD->MODER` to access the `MODER` register.  
* This is called **typecasting the base address** to a structure pointer.

üí° This is **how the structure becomes usable**.

So `((GPIO_TypeDef *) 0x40020C00)` is called **typecasting**:

* You say: ‚ÄúThis address is a pointer to a GPIO\_TypeDef structure.‚Äù

#### **‚úÖ 3\. We access registers using this pointer:**

RCC\-\>AHB1ENR |= GPIOD\_EN; // instead of writing \=, we write |= so that other bits will remain unchanged

GPIOD\-\>MODER |= (1U\<\<26); //set only bit 26 to 1, keep others the same by |=  
GPIOD\-\>MODER &= \~(1U \<\< 27); // set only bit 27 to zero, keep others the same by |= \~

The compiler sees:

‚ÄúOkay, GPIOA is a pointer to a GPIO\_TypeDef. When accessing `->MODER`, I‚Äôll go to address `0x40020000 + 0x00`.‚Äù  
 ‚ÄúWhen accessing `->ODR`, I‚Äôll go to `0x40020000 + 0x14`.‚Äù

üí° All this happens **automatically**, thanks to the struct and the pointer typecasting.
